{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629862"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:10:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:10:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17296"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17296","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17296"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0,0,0.64,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9986"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76199"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9986"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17296"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61703"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1251"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6088"},{"type":"tags","id":"6112"},{"type":"tags","id":"6302"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23395"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76199"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with weakness in his right arm following a fall from a ladder two weeks ago. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His right arm is held in an adducted and internally rotated position at the shoulder joint, with the elbow extended and forearm pronated. There is weakness in shoulder abduction and elbow flexion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best characterises this condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["\u0027Saturday night\u0027 palsy","Bell\u0027s palsy","Typical appearance of claw hand","\u0027Waiter\u0027s tip\u0027 position of arm","Hawkins-Kennedy sign"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003E\u0027waiter\u0027s tip\u0027 position of the arm\u003C/strong\u003E, which is characteristic of Erb\u0027s palsy. This condition results from injury to the upper trunk of the brachial plexus, typically affecting the C5 and C6 nerve roots. These roots contribute to the suprascapular, musculocutaneous and axillary nerves. As a result, their injury leads to the arm being adducted and internally rotated with the elbow extended and forearm pronated. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u0027Saturday night\u0027 palsy\u003C/strong\u003E refers to radial nerve compression at the spiral groove, typically causing wrist drop\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBell\u0027s palsy\u003C/strong\u003E is a lower motor neuron facial nerve palsy affecting facial muscles, not the arm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETypical appearance of claw hand\u003C/strong\u003E occurs with ulnar nerve injury affecting intrinsic hand muscles, not seen in upper trunk injuries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHawkins-Kennedy sign\u003C/strong\u003E is a special test for shoulder impingement syndrome, not a characteristic positio\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erb\u0027s palsy is characterised by the \u0027waiter\u0027s tip\u0027 position of the arm, resulting from injury to the upper trunk of the brachial plexus.","Erb\u0027s palsy typically involves weakness of the shoulder muscles and elbow flexors, leading to an internally rotated and adducted arm with an extended elbow.","The upper trunk (C5-C6) injury of Erb\u0027s palsy affects shoulder abduction and elbow flexion but spares hand function."],"references":["Howard, R., Kullmann, D., Werring, D., \u0026 Zandi, M. (Eds.). (2024). Neurology: a queen square textbook. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Basit H, Ali CDM, Madhani NB. Erb Palsy. 2023 Apr 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30020632."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61703"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17296"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61703"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T12:07:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T12:07:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9986"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76199"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83